I"Î<p>One of the wireless module that comes on the Lenovo T450s or T440s is the Realtek 8192ee, which has bad support out of the box on Arch Linux (or Ubuntu).</p>

<p>The solution that fixed my setup is the following:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Get the latest driver from the repo <a href="https://github.com/lwfinger/rtlwifi_new">https://github.com/lwfinger/rtlwifi_new</a></p>

    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> git clone git@github.com:lwfinger/rtlwifi_new.git
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Compile them on your system</p>

    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> cd rtlwifi_new
 make
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Install them</p>

    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> sudo make install
</code></pre></div>    </div>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Reboot</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p>The kernel module should be automatically loaded when the system boots. If not, load them with the following command</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>sudo modprobe rtl8192ee
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The step <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">3.</code> is to be <strong>repeated after every kernel update</strong>.</p>

<p>If you are still having problem connecting to an encrypted network, add the following options to the module</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>echo "options rtl8192ee swenc=1" &gt; /etc/modprobe.d/rtl8192ee.conf
sudo rmmod rtl8192ee
sudo modprobe rtl8192ee
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Also, according to <a href="https://github.com/mvklingeren">mvklingeren</a>, if you still have problem connecting try to <strong>disable the 802.11n</strong> in your router/access point settings.</p>
:ET